<n-docbody><doc bill="Y"><content.metadata.block><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.second.line.cite><bop/><bos/>Ga. Evidence § 10:12<eos/><eop/></cmd.second.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block><prop.block><prop.head toc-guid=""><bop/><bos/><headtext>Agnor&apos;s Georgia Evidence</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head><content.metadata.block><cmd.dates><cmd.currency.default iso.d="20191101"><bop/><bos/>November 2019 Update<eos/><eop/></cmd.currency.default></cmd.dates></content.metadata.block><author.line><bop/><bos/><author>Ana Marcela Rountree</author><eos/><eop/></author.line><prop.head toc-guid="I295dd720630a11eab5989292d3e01631"><bop/><bos/><label.name>Chapter</label.name><label.designator>10.</label.designator><headtext>Documentary and Demonstrative Evidence</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head></prop.block><message.block><include.copyright n-include_collection="w_wlnv_msg" n-include_guid="I1DA35ED81DD211B281BAD200220BDFCA">Copr. (C) West 2005 No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. Works</include.copyright></message.block><section><section.front><doc.title toc-guid="Id721017a682311ea83aee46e6decbb85"><head parent="doc.title"><bop/><bos/><label.name>§ </label.name><label.designator>10:12.</label.designator><headtext>Electronic records</headtext><eos/><eop/></head></doc.title></section.front><section.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>In 2009, the Georgia legislature repealed the Electronic Records and Signatures Act and replaced it with the Uniform Electronic Transactions Act.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I7ad6cb4074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">1</footnote.reference>] Under the Uniform Electronic Transactions Act, courts and commercial parties are required to treat electronic records and signatures and paper documents the same, although certain rules for the use of electronic documents do apply.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I7ad6cb4174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">2</footnote.reference>] An “electronic record” is any <begin.quote ID="QT_0002"/>“record created, generated, sent, communicated, received, or stored by electronic means.”<eos/><bos/><end.quote refid="QT_0002"/>[<footnote.reference refid="I7ad6cb4274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">3</footnote.reference>] An “electronic signature” is any <begin.quote ID="QT_0001"/>“electronic sound, symbol, or process attached to or logically associated with a record and executed or adopted by a person with the intent to sign the record.”<eos/><bos/><end.quote refid="QT_0001"/>[<footnote.reference refid="I7ad6cb4374d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">4</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>The statute expressly provides that, in legal proceedings, evidence of a record or signature may not be excluded solely because it is in electronic form.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I7ad6f25074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">5</footnote.reference>] If a law requires a record to be in writing or a signature, then an electronic record or signature shall satisfy the law.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I7ad6f25174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">6</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><?page no="364"?><bos/><paratext>An electronic record or electronic signature will be attributable to a person if it was the act of that person. <eos/><bos/>This may be shown in any manner, including through the efficacy of the security procedure applied to determine the person to which the electronic record or signature was attributable.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I7ad6f25274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">7</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>The effect of an electronic record or signature will be determined from the context and surrounding circumstances at the time of its creation, execution, or adoption, including the parties&apos; agreement, if any, and otherwise as provided by law.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I7ad6f25374d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">8</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para></section.body></section><footnote.block><footnote ID="I7ad6cb4074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>1</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017210" w-seq-number="00001" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST10-12-1" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I16997a6074d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">O.C.G.A. §§ 10-12-1 et seq.</cite.query>; 2009 Ga. Laws, Act 141, § 1, eff. July 1, 2009.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I7ad6cb4174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>2</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>See <cite.query w-src-number="0287017210" w-seq-number="00002" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST10-12-3" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I1699c88074d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">O.C.G.A. § 10-12-3</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>This Act does not apply to a transaction to the extent it is governed by (1) a law governing the creation and execution of wills, codicils, or testamentary trusts, (2) Title 11 other than <cite.query w-src-number="0287017210" w-seq-number="00003" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST11-1-107" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I169a3db074d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Code §§ 11-1-107</cite.query> and <cite.query w-src-number="0287017210" w-seq-number="00004" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST11-1-206" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I169a3db174d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">11-1-206</cite.query>, Article 2, and Article 2A, or (3) the Uniform Computer Information Transactions Act. <eos/><bos/><cite.query w-src-number="0287017210" w-seq-number="00005" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST10-12-3" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I169a3db274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">O.C.G.A. § 10-12-3(b)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>The Act also applies only to transactions between parties who have agreed to conduct transactions electronically which is determined from the context, surrounding circumstances, and the parties&apos; conduct. <eos/><bos/><cite.query w-src-number="0287017210" w-seq-number="00006" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST10-12-3" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I169a8bd074d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">O.C.G.A. § 10-12-3(b)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I7ad6cb4274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>3</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017210" w-seq-number="00007" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST10-12-2" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I169ad9f074d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">O.C.G.A. § 10-12-2(7)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I7ad6cb4374d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>4</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017210" w-seq-number="00008" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST10-12-2" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I169b010074d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">O.C.G.A. § 10-12-2(8)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I7ad6f25074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>5</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017210" w-seq-number="00009" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST10-12-13" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I169b4f2074d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">O.C.G.A. § 10-12-13</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I7ad6f25174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>6</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017210" w-seq-number="00010" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST10-12-7" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I169b9d4074d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">O.C.G.A. § 10-12-7(c), (d)</cite.query><?page no="364"?>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I7ad6f25274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>7</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017210" w-seq-number="00011" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST10-12-9" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I169beb6074d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">O.C.G.A. § 10-12-9</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>“Security procedure” means a procedure employed for the purpose of verifying that an electronic signature, record, or performance is that of a specific person or for detecting changes or errors in the information in an electronic record. <eos/><bos/>The term includes a procedure that requires the use of algorithms or other codes, identifying words or numbers, encryption, or callback or other acknowledgment procedures. <eos/><bos/><cite.query w-src-number="0287017210" w-seq-number="00012" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST10-12-2" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I169c87a074d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">O.C.G.A. § 10-12-2(14)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I7ad6f25374d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>8</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017210" w-seq-number="00013" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST10-12-9" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I169cd5c074d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">O.C.G.A. § 10-12-9</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote></footnote.block><content.metadata.block><cmd.royalty><cmd.copyright><bop/><bos/>Westlaw. © 2019 Thomson Reuters.  <eos/><bos/>No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. <eos/><bos/>Works.<eos/><eop/></cmd.copyright></cmd.royalty><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.first.line.cite><bop/><bos/>GAEVIDENCE § 10:12<eos/><eop/></cmd.first.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block></doc></n-docbody>
